      "updated": 1783636927952,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Why backends communicate?\n\n1. Why Move Away from Monoliths? (Microservices)\nAvoid Single Points of Failure: Putting everything (including sensitive data and critical business logic) on a single,\ninternet-exposed server is poor practice.\nSeparation of Concerns: Instead of a single monolith, modern architecture splits the application into smaller,\nindependent services (Microservices) that handle specific jobs.\n\n\n2. Synchronous vs. Asynchronous Tasks\nNot everything needs to happen immediately when a user triggers an action. We categorize tasks into:\nSynchronous (Instant/Core): Must happen right away before responding to the user.\nExample: Deducting money from your account and adding it to the merchant's account.\nAsynchronous (Background/Delayed): Can happen later in the background without making the user wait.\nExample: Sending email/SMS notifications, tracking analytics, or calculating daily dashboard reports.\n\n\n3. How Backends Communicate\nYour primary backend needs a way to talk to other microservices to delegate background work:\nDirect HTTP Call: One server requests another server directly (requires waiting for a response).\nMessage Queues: The primary server pushes tasks to a Queue (e.g., \"T-shirt sold for $20\"), and a worker service\npops and processes them later at its own pace.\nWebSockets: Used for real-time, bi-directional persistent connections.\nPub/Sub (Publisher-Subscriber): The primary server publishes an event (e.g., \"Order Placed\"), and multiple separate\nservices (like Email, SMS, and Analytics) subscribe to and process that event simultaneously.",
      "fontSize": 29.176946015163782,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Why backends communicate?\n\n1. Why Move Away from Monoliths? (Microservices)\nAvoid Single Points of Failure: Putting everything (including sensitive data and critical business logic) on a single, internet-exposed server is poor practice.\nSeparation of Concerns: Instead of a single monolith, modern architecture splits the application into smaller, independent services (Microservices) that handle specific jobs.\n\n\n2. Synchronous vs. Asynchronous Tasks\nNot everything needs to happen immediately when a user triggers an action. We categorize tasks into:\nSynchronous (Instant/Core): Must happen right away before responding to the user.\nExample: Deducting money from your account and adding it to the merchant's account.\nAsynchronous (Background/Delayed): Can happen later in the background without making the user wait.\nExample: Sending email/SMS notifications, tracking analytics, or calculating daily dashboard reports.\n\n\n3. How Backends Communicate\nYour primary backend needs a way to talk to other microservices to delegate background work:\nDirect HTTP Call: One server requests another server directly (requires waiting for a response).\nMessage Queues: The primary server pushes tasks to a Queue (e.g., \"T-shirt sold for $20\"), and a worker service pops and processes them later at its own pace.\nWebSockets: Used for real-time, bi-directional persistent connections.\nPub/Sub (Publisher-Subscriber): The primary server publishes an event (e.g., \"Order Placed\"), and multiple separate services (like Email, SMS, and Analytics) subscribe to and process that event simultaneously.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
