      "updated": 1783636487901,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Backend communication examples?\n\n1. PayTM / Payments (SMS & Email Notifications)\nGoal: Transfer money immediately (DB update: user balance -100, recipient balance +100).\nThe Issue: Sending SMS/Email relies on external services (like Twilio or SendGrid). If these third-party APIs are down\nor slow, you don't want to freeze or fail the transaction.\nThe Queue Solution: The primary backend completes the transaction and pushes a notification task to a Queue (e.g.,\nRabbitMQ or Redis). If the notification service goes offline, the message remains safely in the queue and retries when\nthe service recovers.\n\n2. LeetCode (Code Evaluation & Priority Queues)\nGoal: A user submits code for evaluation.\nThe Issue: Running code is resource-heavy and risky. An infinite loop in the user's code could crash the primary backend.\nThe Queue Solution: The primary backend pushes the code submission to a queue, and separate isolated machines pick it\nup to compile and run.\nPriority Queues:\nPremium Queue: Processed almost instantly (< 3 seconds) using a large pool of fast machines.\nFree Queue: Handled by fewer/smaller machines.\n\n3. Exchanges (Core Execution vs. Heavy Computations)\nGoal: Buy, sell, or withdraw crypto/stocks.\nImmediate (Synchronous): The actual trade matching and execution must happen instantly.\nDelayed (Asynchronous): Volume history updates, reward point calculations, and blockchain withdrawals (which depend on\nslow block confirmation times) are offloaded to background queues.\n\n4. Handling Unreliable Third-Party APIs\nThe Issue: External services (SMS gateways, blockchain networks, email senders) are highly unreliable and experience\nfrequent downtime.\nThe Queue Solution: Using a queue ensures fault tolerance. If a background task fails due to a third-party error, it is\nsimply pushed back into the queue to try again later (retry mechanism).",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Backend communication examples?\n\n1. PayTM / Payments (SMS & Email Notifications)\nGoal: Transfer money immediately (DB update: user balance -100, recipient balance +100).\nThe Issue: Sending SMS/Email relies on external services (like Twilio or SendGrid). If these third-party APIs are down or slow, you don't want to freeze or fail the transaction.\nThe Queue Solution: The primary backend completes the transaction and pushes a notification task to a Queue (e.g., RabbitMQ or Redis). If the notification service goes offline, the message remains safely in the queue and retries when the service recovers.\n\n2. LeetCode (Code Evaluation & Priority Queues)\nGoal: A user submits code for evaluation.\nThe Issue: Running code is resource-heavy and risky. An infinite loop in the user's code could crash the primary backend.\nThe Queue Solution: The primary backend pushes the code submission to a queue, and separate isolated machines pick it up to compile and run.\nPriority Queues:\nPremium Queue: Processed almost instantly (< 3 seconds) using a large pool of fast machines.\nFree Queue: Handled by fewer/smaller machines.\n\n3. Exchanges (Core Execution vs. Heavy Computations)\nGoal: Buy, sell, or withdraw crypto/stocks.\nImmediate (Synchronous): The actual trade matching and execution must happen instantly.\nDelayed (Asynchronous): Volume history updates, reward point calculations, and blockchain withdrawals (which depend on slow block confirmation times) are offloaded to background queues.\n\n4. Handling Unreliable Third-Party APIs\nThe Issue: External services (SMS gateways, blockchain networks, email senders) are highly unreliable and experience frequent downtime.\nThe Queue Solution: Using a queue ensures fault tolerance. If a background task fails due to a third-party error, it is simply pushed back into the queue to try again later (retry mechanism).",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
